Most one-year-old companies don=E2=80=99t have such an experienced team, bu=
t given the growth of the business, the jump from =E2=80=9CCharmander to Ch=
arizard,=E2=80=9D it=E2=80=99s had to grow up quickly and put talent and pr=
ocesses in place befitting an older company.=C2=A0=C2=A0
MainStreet is growing more quickly because of COVID, but for a less direct =
and potentially more sustainable reason than many COVID-growers. Ludlow tol=
d me that while most startups didn=E2=80=99t take PPP, the huge amounts of =
press around the program woke companies up to tax credits and incentives=E2=
=80=99 existence. Plus, in a couple of short years, the conversation around=
 Silicon Valley shifted =E2=80=93 from =E2=80=9Cgrow at all costs,=E2=80=9D=
 to =E2=80=9Cgrow, but be smart about putting every dollar to its best and =
highest use.=E2=80=9D As companies realized they were paying taxes they did=
n=E2=80=99t need to, and that they could apply to growth instead, they=E2=
=80=99ve welcomed MainStreet with open arms.=C2=A0
The majority of MainStreet=E2=80=99s insane revenue growth has come on the =
back of federal R&D credits, but once it plugs into its customers=E2=80=99 =
payroll systems, MainStreet can find new credits and incentives for the sam=
e customer. It has one of the most obvious =E2=80=9Cland-and-expand=E2=80=
=9D strategies in software history available to it: automatically find more=
 pockets of money for customers and take a cut of what it finds.=C2=A0
Historically high growth with low customer acquisition costs (it=E2=80=99s =
not hard to sell companies on =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ll get you your money bac=
k=E2=80=9D), low churn (it=E2=80=99s not hard to convince customers to keep=
 a system that finds them more money running), and obvious revenue expansio=
n opportunities is what venture capitalists dream of. And they=E2=80=99ve c=
ome knocking.=C2=A0
